      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What if I cannot hang for more than 5 seconds on day one?</h3>
          <p>Start with the regression exercises in the beginner dead hang guide for 1-2 weeks before beginning this program. Flexed-arm hangs with feet on a box and partial-weight hangs build the baseline grip strength needed to benefit from the 4-week structure.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>Can I do dead hangs every day instead of 3 times per week?</h3>
          <p>Beginners should stick to 3 sessions per week with rest days between each session. Your finger tendons and forearm connective tissue need 48 hours to recover from near-maximal grip work. Daily training at this stage risks tendonitis and stalled progress.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What should I do if I cannot complete all 3 sets at the target time?</h3>
          <p>Falling 2-3 seconds short on the third set is normal and acceptable. Record your actual times and aim for full target times by your next session. If you consistently miss by more than 5 seconds, repeat the current week before progressing.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq">
          <h3>What happens after I hit 30 seconds on the 4-week program?</h3>
          <p>A 30-second dead hang qualifies you for the 8-week intermediate program which pushes your hold to 60-90 seconds with mixed grip training and 4 sessions per week. If you fell short of 30 seconds, repeat weeks 3 and 4 until you reach the benchmark.</p>
        </div>

